// KOI Content Extension — parsing rule.
//
// Pack:      KoiContentExtension ("KOI Content Extension") v1.0.0.
// Targets:   the koi_koi_raw dataset produced by the OFFICIAL MARKETPLACE
//            KOI pack v1.2.3 (integration id "KOI", 13 commands).
//            This pack ships NO integration of its own.
//
// Binding is by stream, not by pack: XSIAM matches the incoming
// (vendor, product) pair against the [INGEST:] header below. The
// Marketplace integration calls send_events_to_xsiam(vendor="koi",
// product="koi"), so this rule attaches to its stream unchanged.
//
// Strategy: cache the JSON-string form of resources/observables once via a
// chained alter, then use coalesce-of-positions with json_extract_scalar.
// The pattern is identical in normal XQL and in XQLi, so every expression
// here can be pasted into a search bar and prototyped against live rows —
// which is exactly how this version was validated.
//
// 🚨 THE ALERTS STREAM IS MASSIVELY DUPLICATED. Read this before trusting any
// row count in this file. The Marketplace integration re-sends every STILL-OPEN
// alert on every fetch cycle (eventFetchInterval = 1 minute), so koi_koi_raw
// holds one row PER ALERT PER FETCH.
//
// CANONICAL SNAPSHOT — measured 21 July 2026, tenant api-ayman.xdr.eu,
// 90-day window. These are the figures used across the whole pack; do not
// restate this measurement with a different value anywhere else:
//   Alerts, last 24 h : 734 rows ->     3 distinct notifications (~245x)
//   Alerts, last 90 d : 1,048 rows ->  317 distinct notifications (~3.3x)
//   Audit,  last 90 d : 20,148 rows -> 20,148 distinct KOI `id` — NO duplication
//   Alert cohorts, 90 d: 296 extension (none since 2026-07-09) · 842 mcp_server
// Audit is unaffected; this is an Alerts-only defect. Every "N/M" coverage
// figure in the Alerts block below is therefore a count of ROWS, not of alerts,
// and is only meaningful as a ratio. koi_notification_id (promoted below) is
// the column that makes real alert counts possible.
//
// WHY FIGURES IN THIS FILE MUST CARRY A DATE. The dataset gains rows on every
// fetch cycle, so the same query run twenty minutes apart returns different
// absolute numbers — during this validation pass the 90-day Alert row count was
// read as anything from 1,048 to 1,176. None of those readings is wrong; quoting
// one of them as an absolute is. The cohort counts (296 + 842) and the
// whole-stream count (1,048) also came from separate queries and do NOT sum
// exactly. Quote the date with the number, or do not quote the number.
//
// Why coalesce-of-positions instead of arraymap+@element: @element is
// XQLi-only and cannot be tested in XQL. coalesce+if works in both
// contexts, so we keep a tight test loop.
//
// Position bounds — LIVE-VERIFIED 21 July 2026, do not tighten:
//   observables max length 7 (idx 0..6); rule scans 0..7 -> 1 spare slot.
//   resources   max length 3 (idx 0..2); rule scans 0..3 -> 1 spare slot.
// The coalesce-by-type design is REQUIRED, not stylistic. Live layout of
// `resources`, 90 days, 21 July 2026:
//   842 rows: [0]=mcp,  [1]=device                    (mcp_server alerts)
//   296 rows: [0]=item, [1]=device, [2]=item_instance (extension alerts)
// So a fixed index 0 would read MCP data on ~74% of rows today and item data on
// the rest — and the split moves as the population shifts (see the item/MCP
// note in the resources[type="item"] block). Match on .type, never on position.

[INGEST:vendor="koi", product="koi", target_dataset="koi_koi_raw", no_hit=keep]
// Audit rows only. The filter is LOAD-BEARING: created_at is present on
// 20,148/20,148 audit rows but NULL on all 1,048 alert rows (90 days,
// 21 July 2026), so applying this unguarded would null _time on every alert.
// (Alerts take _time from
// finding_info.created_time, which the integration already sets.)
// Live check: _time already equals created_at truncated to whole seconds on
// 100/100 sampled audit rows, so this assignment is currently a no-op. It is
// kept as a cheap guard against an integration change — it is NOT a fix for
// a broken timestamp, and must not be described as one.
filter source_log_type = "Audit"
| alter _time = created_at
// ── marketplace_api — NEW. The Audit twin of item_marketplace_api below. ──
// Same defect, same fix, same vocabulary table; see the long comment on
// item_marketplace_api at the foot of the Alerts block for the full rationale.
//
// Worth adding here? Yes, and by a wide margin. Live check on the raw `marketplace`
// column, 90 days, 21 July 2026: ~13,850 of the 20,148 audit rows carry a value
// (repeated readings the same day ranged 13,800–13,849 as the dataset grew; the
// PROPORTIONS did not move, and they are what this note is about). The
// SINGLE MOST COMMON value — software_windows, 5,294 rows — is a short form the API
// rejects with HTTP 400. Ranked: software_windows 5,294 · pypi 4,674 · chrome 891 ·
// built_in 828 · npm 775 · software_mac 617 · homebrew 231 · vsc 175 · chocolatey 91 ·
// cursor 88 · github 65 · edge 48 · firefox 19 · docker 15 · npp 12 · openvsx 10 ·
// jet 5 · claude_desktop_extensions 5 · ollama 5 · side_loaded 1 · (null ~6,300).
// So ~7,136 of the ~13,850 populated rows (52%) would 400 if passed through unchanged.
// An audit-driven flow is exactly the case that breaks on the most common value in
// the whole dataset.
//
// `marketplace` itself is UNTOUCHED — it stays the verbatim Koi event value.
| alter marketplace_api = if(
    marketplace = "software_windows", "windows",
    marketplace = "software_mac",     "mac",
    marketplace = "chrome",           "chrome_web_store",
    marketplace = "edge",             "edge_add_ons",
    marketplace = "firefox",          "firefox_add_ons",
    marketplace = "vsc",              "vscode",
    marketplace = "jet",              "jetbrains",
    marketplace = "npp",              "notepad++",
    marketplace = "openvsx",          "open_vsx_registry",
    marketplace = "github",           "github_mcp_registry",
    // Already-API values pass through unchanged. This whitelist is the complete
    // `predefined` list of the marketplace argument in Koi.yml v1.2.3 (all 22
    // values, on all 7 commands that take the argument) — verified against
    // reference/marketplace-pack.json, not typed from memory.
    marketplace in ("chocolatey", "chrome_web_store", "claude_desktop_extensions", "cursor",
                    "docker", "edge_add_ons", "firefox_add_ons", "github_mcp_registry",
                    "homebrew", "hugging_face", "jetbrains", "linux", "mac", "notepad++",
                    "npm", "office_add_ins", "open_vsx_registry", "pypi", "visual_studio",
                    "vscode", "windows", "windsurf"), marketplace,
    // Everything else -> NULL, deliberately. built_in (828) and side_loaded (1) are
    // installation_method values leaking into the marketplace field; ollama (5) is
    // absent from the API's list entirely. All three are "unknown marketplace" and
    // must never reach a command argument.
    to_string(null));

filter source_log_type = "Alerts"
| alter
    // finding_info — single JSON object, no cast needed. All 3 resolve on
    // 100% of alert rows on live data (1,048/1,048, 90 d, 21 July 2026), and
    // all 3 are non-empty on every one of those rows.
    //
    // ⚠️ finding_uid IS A POLICY ID, NOT AN ALERT ID. 3 distinct values across
    // 1,040 alerts: 20940 "MCP Servers alerts", 23300 "NPM Block CS",
    // 20907 "yito test". It identifies the FINDING DEFINITION that fired,
    // shared by every alert the same policy ever raises. It is a perfectly good
    // queryable column for "which policy is noisy" and that is ALL it is. It was
    // mapped to xdm.alert.original_alert_id until 21 July 2026; THAT MAPPING HAS
    // BEEN REMOVED AND MUST NOT BE RE-ADDED — see the DO-NOT-RE-ADD note at the
    // site in the sibling modeling rule, and the "removed mappings" table in
    // this directory's README.md. Koi supplies no per-alert vendor identifier on
    // this stream, so the XDM field stays empty on purpose.
    finding_uid           = json_extract_scalar(finding_info, "$.uid"),
    finding_title         = json_extract_scalar(finding_info, "$.title"),
    finding_created_time  = json_extract_scalar(finding_info, "$.created_time"),
    // NOT PROMOTED: finding_info.desc. It resolves on 293 of 1,048 rows (~28%,
    // 21 July 2026) and
    // those 293 are exactly the rows where finding_title = "NPM Block CS" — i.e.
    // the field is POLICY-DEPENDENT, present only when the policy author wrote a
    // description. It is not a universal alert attribute, so promoting it would
    // create a column that looks general and is not. Reach for it inline
    // (json_extract_scalar(finding_info, "$.desc")) if you are already scoped to
    // one policy.
    // finding_info.types has array_length = 1 on 100% of rows (1,048/1,048,
    // 21 July 2026), so arrayindex(...,0)
    // discards nothing. NOTE: alert_type has exactly ONE distinct value in 90
    // days of live data — "policy_violation". Anything downstream that branches
    // on alert_type has nothing to branch on today. (This column is created
    // here; the raw koi_koi_raw column of the same name is always null.)
    alert_type            = arrayindex(json_extract_scalar_array(finding_info, "$.types"), 0),
    // ── metadata — a PLAIN OBJECT, not an array ────────────────────────
    // Live shape, verbatim: {"version":"1.7.0","product":{"name":"Koi",
    // "vendor_name":"Koi"},"notification_event_id":"84d52bf1-…"}. Because it is
    // a plain object, a single json_extract_scalar suffices — no to_json_string
    // cache and no coalesce-of-positions. Do not "make it consistent" with the
    // array handling above; that would be pure cost.
    //
    // 🔑 koi_notification_id IS THE DEDUPE KEY. DO NOT REMOVE IT AS REDUNDANT.
    // The integration re-sends every still-open alert on every 1-minute fetch,
    // so a row is a FETCH, not an alert. Measured 21 July 2026, 90 days:
    //   1,048 rows -> 317 distinct notification_event_id (~3.3x). 317 held
    //   steady across repeated measurements while the row count grew.
    //   Last 24 h: 734 rows -> 3 distinct. That is ~245x inflation.
    // Candidate keys, same window, so nobody re-litigates this:
    //   _id                     1,048 distinct — the ROW; counts every duplicate
    //   koi_notification_id       317 distinct — the ALERT OCCURRENCE ✅
    //   koi_event_id               20 distinct — the SCAN BATCH; far too coarse
    //   finding_uid                 3 distinct — the POLICY; not an identity
    // Hierarchy: scan batch (20) ⊃ notification (317) ⊃ rows (1,048).
    // notification_event_id is a verified 1:1 identity for the tuple
    // (item.id, device.id, finding_info.uid, finding_info.created_time) —
    // 317 ids, 317 tuples, zero collisions in either direction.
    //
    // CONSEQUENCE: every widget, report or playbook that counts alerts must use
    // count_distinct(koi_notification_id). A plain count() over Alerts is wrong
    // by two orders of magnitude — 734 versus 3 over the last 24 h.
    // Note the duplication is not uniform: over 90 days the 296 extension rows
    // carry 296 distinct notifications (1.0x, none) while the 842 mcp_server
    // rows carry 21 (~40x). The MCP cohort is the one being re-sent, because
    // those are the alerts that stay open.
    // 100% populated and non-empty on every alert row (21 July 2026).
    // On HISTORICAL rows this column is null — parsing rules apply at ingest
    // only — so dedupe over old data with the inline
    // json_extract_scalar(metadata, "$.notification_event_id"). That is what the
    // dashboard widgets do.
    koi_notification_id   = json_extract_scalar(metadata, "$.notification_event_id"),
    // koi_product_version — A CHANGE DETECTOR, NOT AN ANALYTIC DIMENSION.
    // Constant "1.7.0" on 100% of alert rows (1 distinct value across the 1,048
    // rows of the 21 July 2026 snapshot), so it partitions
    // nothing and no dashboard should group by it. It is promoted because this
    // pack has already been burned once by an UNDATED, UNANNOUNCED Koi-side
    // change — koi_tenant_name / koi_customer_id stopped being emitted mid-July
    // 2026 and the only way to date the cut-over was to bisect _insert_time by
    // hand (see the regression note in the modeling rule). With this column,
    // that class of investigation becomes one query:
    //   comp count(), min(_time), max(_time) by koi_product_version
    // The day it stops reading 1.7.0, the payload shape may have moved and every
    // extraction in this file is worth re-validating.
    koi_product_version   = json_extract_scalar(metadata, "$.version"),
    // Cache the JSON-string form of the array-typed columns.
    // NOTE: on this dataset `resources` and `observables` are ALREADY JSON
    // strings, so to_json_string() is a verbatim identity no-op (verified
    // byte-for-byte on every alert row). This stage CACHES, it does not normalise —
    // and it is what makes the rule prototypable in plain XQL.
    resources_str         = to_json_string(resources),
    observables_str       = to_json_string(observables)
| alter
    // ── observables[] — match by .name across positions 0..7 ───────────
    // The complete set of observable .name keys on live data is exactly 7:
    // event.id, device.os, device.serial, item.id, item.version, item.type,
    // item.marketplace. All 7 are promoted below.
    item_id = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.0.name")="item.id", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.0.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.1.name")="item.id", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.1.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.2.name")="item.id", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.2.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.3.name")="item.id", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.3.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.4.name")="item.id", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.4.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.5.name")="item.id", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.5.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.6.name")="item.id", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.6.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.7.name")="item.id", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.7.value"), null)),
    item_type = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.0.name")="item.type", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.0.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.1.name")="item.type", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.1.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.2.name")="item.type", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.2.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.3.name")="item.type", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.3.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.4.name")="item.type", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.4.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.5.name")="item.type", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.5.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.6.name")="item.type", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.6.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.7.name")="item.type", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.7.value"), null)),
    // ⚠️ alert_item_version — EMPTY-STRING GUARDED. Do not simplify this back to
    // a bare coalesce. MCP alerts carry the observable {"name":"item.version",
    // "value":""} — the KEY IS PRESENT, so the value passes every `!= null` test
    // while being useless. Live, 90 days, 21 July 2026:
    //   extension  :   296 rows, 296 non-null, 296 genuinely populated
    //   mcp_server :   842 rows, 842 non-null,  11 genuinely populated (1.3%)
    // Ungrouped that is 831 empty strings masquerading as data on ~73% of alert
    // rows — a "group by item version" widget produces one giant blank bucket.
    // The coalesce below is UNCHANGED; the guard is a SAME-NAME REASSIGNMENT in
    // a later alter stage (see "alert_item_version — empty-string guard" further
    // down), because a column cannot be read in the stage that creates it. That
    // keeps this chain readable and adds no extra dataset column.
    // Post-guard, live-validated 21 July 2026: 307 populated, ZERO empty
    // strings, 253 distinct versions — extension 296/296 unchanged,
    // mcp_server 842 -> 11. Nothing that had a value lost one.
    //
    // This is the ONLY column in the pack with this defect. Every other promoted
    // alert column was re-tested with `x != null and x != ""` on 21 July 2026 and
    // came back with zero empty strings — see the audit list at the foot of this
    // file. Test both conditions when you add a column; `!= null` alone is not
    // a population check on this feed.
    alert_item_version = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.0.name")="item.version", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.0.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.1.name")="item.version", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.1.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.2.name")="item.version", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.2.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.3.name")="item.version", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.3.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.4.name")="item.version", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.4.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.5.name")="item.version", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.5.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.6.name")="item.version", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.6.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.7.name")="item.version", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.7.value"), null)),
    // item_marketplace — NEW in this pack. Populated on 296 rows (npm 293,
    // chrome 3), zero empty strings; absent on the 842 mcp_server rows, which
    // carry no item.marketplace observable.
    // ⚠️ COVERAGE RESTATED 21 July 2026: this used to read "296/314 (94%)". The
    // alert population has SHIFTED — see the item/MCP note in the
    // resources[type="item"] block — and it is now 296 of 1,048 rows (~28%,
    // 21 July 2026), with NO extension alert since 2026-07-09. The column is NOT
    // broken; the cohort that populates it has stopped arriving and may return.
    // Operationally important: `marketplace` is a
    // REQUIRED argument on koi-inventory-item-get and
    // koi-inventory-item-endpoints-list, and nothing else in the alert payload
    // supplies it. Without this column an alert cannot be enriched back
    // through the Marketplace integration's item-scoped commands.
    //
    // ⚠️ This column is the RAW EVENT value and is in the SHORT vocabulary.
    // Do NOT pass it to a command — pass item_marketplace_api (added at the
    // foot of this block) instead. Both are kept on purpose: the raw value is
    // what the event said, the _api value is what the API accepts, and
    // conflating the two is precisely the bug this pack exists to avoid.
    item_marketplace = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.0.name")="item.marketplace", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.0.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.1.name")="item.marketplace", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.1.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.2.name")="item.marketplace", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.2.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.3.name")="item.marketplace", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.3.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.4.name")="item.marketplace", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.4.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.5.name")="item.marketplace", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.5.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.6.name")="item.marketplace", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.6.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.7.name")="item.marketplace", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.7.value"), null)),
    device_os_obs = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.0.name")="device.os", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.0.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.1.name")="device.os", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.1.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.2.name")="device.os", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.2.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.3.name")="device.os", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.3.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.4.name")="device.os", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.4.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.5.name")="device.os", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.5.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.6.name")="device.os", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.6.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.7.name")="device.os", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.7.value"), null)),
    device_serial = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.0.name")="device.serial", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.0.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.1.name")="device.serial", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.1.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.2.name")="device.serial", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.2.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.3.name")="device.serial", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.3.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.4.name")="device.serial", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.4.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.5.name")="device.serial", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.5.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.6.name")="device.serial", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.6.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.7.name")="device.serial", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.7.value"), null)),
    // koi_event_id — populated on every alert row and never empty, but only
    // 20 DISTINCT values across 1,048 rows (re-measured 21 July 2026): it is a
    // per-SCAN-BATCH UUID, not a per-occurrence one (~52 rows share each value).
    // It is promoted as a BATCH CORRELATOR only.
    // It is NOT the dedupe key either — the batch is COARSER than the alert:
    // 20 batches ⊃ 317 notifications ⊃ 1,048 rows. Use koi_notification_id to
    // count alerts, koi_event_id only to ask "what else came in this scan".
    // It is deliberately NOT used as xdm.event.id in the modeling rule —
    // see KoiContentExtension ModelingRules.
    koi_event_id = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.0.name")="event.id", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.0.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.1.name")="event.id", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.1.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.2.name")="event.id", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.2.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.3.name")="event.id", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.3.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.4.name")="event.id", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.4.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.5.name")="event.id", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.5.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.6.name")="event.id", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.6.value"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.7.name")="event.id", json_extract_scalar(observables_str, "$.7.value"), null)),

    // ── resources[] where .type="device" — positions 0..3 ──────────────
    // All six below verified on 100% of alert rows (1,048/1,048), zero empty
    // strings (90 d, 21 July 2026). They are the only alert columns that
    // populate across BOTH the extension and mcp_server cohorts.
    // NOTE for anyone tempted to map alert_hostname to xdm.target.host.fqdn:
    // that mapping existed and was REMOVED 21 July 2026. Hostnames contain a dot
    // on 0 of 1,138 rows — they are bare names. Do not re-add it.
    device_id = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.data.id"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.data.id"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.data.id"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.data.id"), null)),
    alert_hostname = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.data.hostname"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.data.hostname"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.data.hostname"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.data.hostname"), null)),
    device_last_seen = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.data.last_seen"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.data.last_seen"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.data.last_seen"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.data.last_seen"), null)),
    device_last_user = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.data.last_logged_on_user"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.data.last_logged_on_user"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.data.last_logged_on_user"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.data.last_logged_on_user"), null)),
    device_status = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.data.status"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.data.status"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.data.status"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.data.status"), null)),
    device_registered_at = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.data.registered_at"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.data.registered_at"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.data.registered_at"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.type")="device", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.data.registered_at"), null)),
    // DROPPED: device_network_user (was resources[device].data.network_user).
    // The key exists on every device resource but its value is literally null
    // on every alert row. Not emitted by Koi as of 2026-07.

    // ── resources[] where .type="item" — positions 0..3 ────────────────
    // NEW in this pack. The custom pack's rule never touched
    // resources[type="item"] at all, and when this pack added it that block was
    // the largest untapped surface in the payload.
    //
    // ⚠️ THE ALERT POPULATION HAS SHIFTED — READ BEFORE "FIXING" THESE COLUMNS.
    // Measured 21 July 2026 over 90 days; the earlier figure in this comment
    // ("296 of 314, 94%") is stale and is corrected here:
    //   extension  :   296 rows | LAST SEEN 2026-07-09 — nothing for 12 days
    //   mcp_server :   842 rows | current; effectively 100% of live ingestion
    // So item_package_name, item_risk_level, item_criticality, item_marketplace
    // and (downstream) xdm.target.resource.sub_type are NULL ON ALL CURRENT DATA.
    // That is 296 of 1,048 rows (~28%), not 94%.
    //
    // THESE COLUMNS ARE KEPT DELIBERATELY. They are not broken mappings — the
    // cohort that populates them stopped arriving and may return the moment an
    // extension policy fires again. Do not delete them because a 24-hour query
    // shows them empty.
    //
    // NOT a substitute: resources[type=mcp].data.marketplace exists on MCP
    // alerts and is already in the API long vocabulary, but it is the EMPTY
    // STRING on ~99% of the MCP cohort (measured 21 July 2026; the reading was
    // 705 of 716 rows on one query and 843 of 854 on a later one — the RATIO is
    // the stable fact). Wiring it in would need an explicit `!= ""` guard and
    // would still cover ~1% of that cohort, so it is left unpromoted.
    //
    // All three below verified on 296/296 extension rows, zero empty strings
    // (null on the 842 mcp_server rows, which carry no "item" resource).
    item_package_name = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.type")="item", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.data.package_name"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.type")="item", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.data.package_name"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.type")="item", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.data.package_name"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.type")="item", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.data.package_name"), null)),
    item_risk_level = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.type")="item", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.data.risk_level"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.type")="item", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.data.risk_level"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.type")="item", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.data.risk_level"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.type")="item", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.data.risk_level"), null)),
    // item_criticality lives on the resource WRAPPER, not under .data —
    // same shape as mcp_criticality below.
    item_criticality = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.type")="item", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.criticality"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.type")="item", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.criticality"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.type")="item", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.criticality"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.type")="item", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.criticality"), null)),

    // ── resources[] where .type="mcp" — positions 0..3 ─────────────────
    // ⚠️ DENOMINATOR CORRECTED 21 July 2026. This block used to say "the 18 MCP
    // alerts". It is now 842 mcp_server ROWS over 90 days — but see the
    // duplication banner at the top of this file: those 842 rows are only 21
    // distinct notifications. The MCP cohort is both the largest AND the most
    // heavily re-sent. Every "N/842" below is a ROW count.
    // All eight columns below verified zero empty strings on 21 July 2026.
    mcp_id = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.data.mcp_id"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.data.mcp_id"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.data.mcp_id"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.data.mcp_id"), null)),
    mcp_package_name = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.data.package_name"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.data.package_name"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.data.package_name"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.data.package_name"), null)),
    mcp_type = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.data.mcp_type"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.data.mcp_type"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.data.mcp_type"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.data.mcp_type"), null)),
    mcp_transport = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.data.transport"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.data.transport"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.data.transport"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.data.transport"), null)),
    // mcp_url is CORRECTLY SPARSE, not broken: populated on 2 of the 842 mcp rows,
    // exactly the rows where mcp_type = "remote" (a local stdio MCP server has
    // no URL). The absolute count has not moved as the cohort grew, which is
    // itself the evidence that remote MCP servers are genuinely rare here.
    // Keep it — it is the only network indicator on an MCP alert.
    mcp_url = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.data.url"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.data.url"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.data.url"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.data.url"), null)),
    mcp_risk_level = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.data.risk_level"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.data.risk_level"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.data.risk_level"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.data.risk_level"), null)),
    mcp_risk_status = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.data.risk_status"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.data.risk_status"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.data.risk_status"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.data.risk_status"), null)),
    // DROPPED: mcp_package_type (was resources[mcp].data.package_type) and
    // mcp_installation_method (was resources[mcp].data.installation_method).
    // Neither key exists under .data on any MCP resource — 0 of 842 rows,
    // re-checked 21 July 2026 against the far larger current cohort. The
    // complete observed .data key set is: mcp_id, name, version, marketplace,
    // mcp_type, transport, package_name, risk_level, risk_status, risk, url.
    // Not emitted by Koi as of 2026-07.
    //
    // mcp_criticality lives on the resource WRAPPER, not under .data.
    mcp_criticality = coalesce(
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.0.criticality"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.1.criticality"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.2.criticality"), null),
        if(json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.type")="mcp", json_extract_scalar(resources_str, "$.3.criticality"), null))
// ── alert_item_version — empty-string guard. ───────────────────────────────
// A SEPARATE alter stage, and a SAME-NAME REASSIGNMENT: alert_item_version is
// created by the stage above and a column cannot be read in the stage that
// creates it. The full rationale is on the coalesce itself — short version:
// MCP alerts send {"name":"item.version","value":""}, so the key is present and
// `!= null` passes on 100% of rows while ~73% of them hold nothing (831 of the
// 842 mcp_server rows, 90 days, 21 July 2026).
//
// DO NOT DELETE THIS STAGE. Without it every population audit, every
// "group by version" widget and every playbook branch that tests
// `alert_item_version != null` is wrong on the entire MCP cohort — which is
// effectively all current ingestion.
//
// Live-validated 21 July 2026 (90 d): before, non-null on 100% of alert rows of
// which 831 were the empty string; after, 307 populated, 0 empty, 253 distinct.
// Extension rows are untouched (296 -> 296); the mcp_server cohort drops
// 842 -> 11, which is the true count.
| alter alert_item_version = if(alert_item_version != "", alert_item_version, to_string(null))
// ── item_marketplace_api — NEW. The command-safe marketplace value. ─────────
// A SEPARATE alter stage because it consumes item_marketplace, which is created
// by the stage above. Same reason the resources_str/observables_str cache is its
// own stage.
//
// WHY THIS EXISTS. The event vocabulary and the API vocabulary are DIFFERENT.
// `marketplace` is a REQUIRED argument on koi-inventory-item-get,
// koi-inventory-item-endpoints-list and koi-blocklist-items-add; feeding it the
// raw event value returns HTTP 400 on every value except npm and pypi.
// Verified 21 July 2026 by testing each value against GET /inventory?marketplace=.
//
// Frequencies across the whole dataset (90 days, both source_log_types), kept
// here so a future editor can see which branches are load-bearing:
//   software_windows 5,301 -> windows              chrome  891 -> chrome_web_store
//   pypi   4,674 -> pypi (unchanged)               npm     775 -> npm (unchanged)
//   software_mac       617 -> mac                  homebrew 231 -> homebrew
//   vsc                175 -> vscode               chocolatey 91 -> chocolatey
//   cursor              88 -> cursor               github    65 -> github_mcp_registry
//   edge                48 -> edge_add_ons         firefox   19 -> firefox_add_ons
//   docker              15 -> docker               npp       12 -> notepad++
//   openvsx             10 -> open_vsx_registry    jet        5 -> jetbrains
//   claude_desktop_extensions 5 -> unchanged
//   built_in 829 · ollama 5 · side_loaded 1 -> NULL, no API equivalent.
//
// ON ALERTS SPECIFICALLY the exposure is small but real: item_marketplace is
// npm on 293 rows and chrome on 3 — 296 of 1,048 alert rows (~28%, corrected
// 21 July 2026 from a stale "296 of 314"); null on the 842 mcp_server rows,
// which carry no item.marketplace observable. Only the 3 chrome rows are wrong
// today — but they are wrong 100% of the time, and silently. Note that no
// extension alert has arrived since 2026-07-09, so on CURRENT data this whole
// branch is dormant rather than busy; it is kept for when the cohort returns.
//
// EVIDENCE THAT THE MAPPING TABLE IS RIGHT, not merely plausible: the alert
// payload carries the SAME field twice in TWO DIFFERENT vocabularies.
// observables[name="item.marketplace"] is the short form; the item resource
// (resources[type="item"].data.marketplace) is already the API long form. On the
// same rows, live: obs=npm/res=npm on 293, and obs=chrome/res=chrome_web_store
// on 3. So Koi itself states chrome -> chrome_web_store in its own payload, and
// the map below reproduces the vendor's own answer on 296/296 rows. (Caveat,
// stated rather than glossed: that cross-check covers the 2 distinct values that
// occur on alerts. The other 8 short forms are verified against the API's 400/200
// responses, not against the resource block.)
//
// The map is idempotent: an already-long value falls through to the whitelist
// branch and is returned unchanged. That is why it is safe to point this same
// expression at either vocabulary.
| alter item_marketplace_api = if(
    item_marketplace = "software_windows", "windows",
    item_marketplace = "software_mac",     "mac",
    item_marketplace = "chrome",           "chrome_web_store",
    item_marketplace = "edge",             "edge_add_ons",
    item_marketplace = "firefox",          "firefox_add_ons",
    item_marketplace = "vsc",              "vscode",
    item_marketplace = "jet",              "jetbrains",
    item_marketplace = "npp",              "notepad++",
    item_marketplace = "openvsx",          "open_vsx_registry",
    item_marketplace = "github",           "github_mcp_registry",
    // All 22 values of the `marketplace` argument's predefined list in Koi.yml
    // v1.2.3, taken from reference/marketplace-pack.json. Already-API values
    // pass through unchanged.
    item_marketplace in ("chocolatey", "chrome_web_store", "claude_desktop_extensions", "cursor",
                         "docker", "edge_add_ons", "firefox_add_ons", "github_mcp_registry",
                         "homebrew", "hugging_face", "jetbrains", "linux", "mac", "notepad++",
                         "npm", "office_add_ins", "open_vsx_registry", "pypi", "visual_studio",
                         "vscode", "windows", "windsurf"), item_marketplace,
    // NULL means "unknown marketplace" — built_in / side_loaded (installation
    // methods, not marketplaces) and ollama (not in the API's list at all).
    // A playbook must treat null here as "cannot call an item-scoped command",
    // NOT as "try the raw value instead".
    to_string(null));

// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
// EMPTY-STRING AUDIT — ALL 31 promoted Alerts columns, 90 days, 21 July 2026.
// This table is EXHAUSTIVE: if you add a column above, add a row here.
// Tested with BOTH conditions (`x != null` AND `x != ""`), because on this feed
// the first alone is not a population check. Reproduce with:
//   ... | comp sum(if(col != null, 1, 0)) as nn, sum(if(col = "", 1, 0)) as mt
//
// Denominators are the canonical 21 July 2026 snapshot from the banner at the
// top of this file: 1,048 alert rows over 90 days, of which 296 are the
// extension cohort and 842 the mcp_server cohort. Whole-stream and per-cohort
// figures came from separate queries and do NOT sum exactly — the dataset gains
// rows on every fetch cycle. What each row asserts is the RATIO (100% of rows,
// or 100% of one cohort), and the ratios are stable.
//
//   column                  populated  empty ""   verdict
//   ─────────────────────── ────────── ────────── ─────────────────────────────
//   finding_uid              1,048          0     clean (3 distinct = policy id)
//   finding_title            1,048          0     clean
//   finding_created_time     1,048          0     clean
//   alert_type               1,048          0     clean (1 distinct)
//   koi_notification_id      1,048          0     clean (317 distinct) ← key
//   koi_product_version      1,048          0     clean (1 distinct, "1.7.0")
//   item_id                  1,048          0     clean
//   item_type                1,048          0     clean
//   alert_item_version       1,048        831     ⚠️ GUARDED ABOVE -> 307 / 0
//   item_marketplace           296          0     clean (extension cohort only)
//   item_marketplace_api       296          0     clean (extension cohort only)
//   device_os_obs            1,048          0     clean
//   device_serial            1,048          0     clean
//   koi_event_id             1,048          0     clean (20 distinct = batch)
//   device_id                1,048          0     clean
//   alert_hostname           1,048          0     clean (0 contain a dot —
//                                          that is why fqdn is unmapped)
//   device_last_seen         1,048          0     clean
//   device_last_user         1,048          0     clean
//   device_status            1,048          0     clean
//   device_registered_at     1,048          0     clean
//   item_package_name          296          0     clean (extension cohort only)
//   item_risk_level            296          0     clean (extension cohort only)
//   item_criticality           296          0     clean (extension cohort only)
//   mcp_id                     842          0     clean (mcp cohort only)
//   mcp_package_name           842          0     clean (mcp cohort only)
//   mcp_type                   842          0     clean (mcp cohort only)
//   mcp_transport              842          0     clean (mcp cohort only)
//   mcp_url                      2          0     clean (correctly sparse)
//   mcp_risk_level             842          0     clean (mcp cohort only)
//   mcp_risk_status            842          0     clean (mcp cohort only)
//   mcp_criticality            842          0     clean (mcp cohort only)
//   ─────────────────────── ────────── ────────── ─────────────────────────────
//   31 columns. Plus 2 working intermediates that also persist as dataset
//   columns and are not audited here: resources_str / observables_str.
//   The Audit statement's marketplace_api is audited with the Audit block, not
//   here — this table is the ALERTS surface.
//
// ON item_marketplace_api SPECIFICALLY (added to this table 21 July 2026, having
// been omitted while the table claimed to be exhaustive): it is PROVABLY SAFE
// without a live re-measurement. It is a pure function of item_marketplace, and
// every branch of that function returns either a non-empty literal, a
// non-empty passthrough of item_marketplace, or to_string(null). There is no
// path that yields "". An empty item_marketplace would match NO branch — not the
// ten equality tests, not the 22-value whitelist — and fall through to
// to_string(null); and item_marketplace itself has zero empty strings (row
// above). So: 296 populated, 0 empty, matching its source column exactly
// (293 npm -> npm, 3 chrome -> chrome_web_store).
//
// Not promoted, and why:
//   finding_info.desc               293/1,048 — POLICY-DEPENDENT (only
//                                   "NPM Block CS"), not a universal attribute.
//   resources[mcp].data.marketplace non-null across the mcp cohort but ~99%
//                                   EMPTY — fails the empty-string test, so it
//                                   is not a substitute for item_marketplace.
//   resources[item_instance].*      present at position 2 on extension rows;
//                                   unexamined, out of scope for this pass.
// ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
